    "summary": "The Munich Agreement, signed on September 30, 1938, by Germany, Britain, France, and Italy, forced Czechoslovakia to cede the Sudetenland — its ethnically German-speaking border regions — to [[event:2653|Nazi Germany]]. The agreement was the culmination of British and French appeasement policy, seeking to satisfy Hitler's territorial demands and avoid another European war. British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain returned from Munich declaring that he had secured peace for our time — a phrase that became permanently associated with the failure of appeasement.\n\nCzechoslovakia was not represented at the conference and was not consulted about the decision to cede its territory. The Sudetenland contained Czechoslovakia's most formidable defensive fortifications and significant industrial resources. Its loss made the remaining Czech state militarily indefensible. In March 1939, Germany violated the Munich Agreement by occupying the rest of Bohemia and Moravia. Slovakia was established as a nominally independent puppet state. The occupation of non-German Czechoslovakia destroyed the argument that Hitler's ambitions were limited to unifying ethnic Germans.\n\nMunich became the defining symbol of appeasement's failure. The lesson drawn by Western statesmen — that dictators cannot be satisfied through territorial concessions — became a persistent influence on subsequent foreign policy, though historians debate whether the agreement was the strategic blunder it appears in hindsight or whether it bought time for Allied rearmament.",
